Stock

Slot Description
1 Name The name of the Stock object. Single value. Character string
2 Common_Name Common name of the species. Character string
3 Species Scientific name of the species. Genus and species name. Character string
4 maxage The maximum age of individuals that is simulated (there is no plus group ). Single value. Positive integer
5 R0 The magnitude of unfished recruitment. Single value. Positive real number
6 M Natural mortality rate. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real number
7 M2 (Optional) Natural mortality rate at age. Vector of length maxage . Positive real number
8 Mexp Exponent of the Lorenzen function assuming an inverse relationship between M and weight. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers <= 0.
9 Msd Inter-annual variability in natural mortality rate expressed as a coefficient of variation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
10 Mgrad Mean temporal trend in natural mortality rate, expressed as a percentage change in M per year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
11 h Steepness of the stock recruit relationship. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Values from 1/5 to 1
12 SRrel Type of stock-recruit relationship. Single value, switch (1) Beverton-Holt (2) Ricker. Integer
13 Perr Process error, the CV of lognormal recruitment deviations. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
14 AC Autocorrelation in recruitment deviations rec(t)=ACrec(t-1)+(1-AC)sigma(t). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
15 Period (Optional) Period for cyclical recruitment pattern in years. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
16 Amplitude (Optional) Amplitude in deviation from long-term average recruitment during recruitment cycle (eg a range from 0 to 1 means recruitment decreases or increases by up to 100% each cycle). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. 0 < Amplitude < 1
17 Linf Maximum length. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
18 K von Bertalanffy growth parameter k. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
19 t0 von Bertalanffy theoretical age at length zero. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-positive real numbers
20 LenCV Coefficient of variation of length-at-age (assumed constant for all age classes). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
21 Ksd Inter-annual variability in growth parameter k. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
22 Kgrad Mean temporal trend in growth parameter k, expressed as a percentage change in k per year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
23 Linfsd Inter-annual variability in maximum length. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
24 Linfgrad Mean temporal trend in maximum length, expressed as a percentage change in Linf per year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
25 L50 Length at 50 percent maturity. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
26 L50_95 Length increment from 50 percent to 95 percent maturity. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
27 D Current level of stock depletion SSB(current)/SSB(unfished). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Fraction
28 a Length-weight parameter alpha. Single value. Positive real number
29 b Length-weight parameter beta. Single value. Positive real number
30 Size_area_1 The size of area 1 relative to area 2. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
31 Frac_area_1 The fraction of the unfished biomass in stock 1. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
32 Prob_staying The probability of inviduals in area 1 remaining in area 1 over the course of one year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive fraction.
33 Fdisc Fraction of discarded fish that die. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
34 Source A reference to a website or article from which parameters were taken to define the stock object. Single value. Character string.
36 NA
38 NA
40 NA

Fleet

Slot Description
1 Name Name of the Fleet object. Single value. Character string.
2 nyears The number of years for the historical spool-up simulation. Single value. Positive integer
3 Spat_targ Distribution of fishing in relation to spatial biomass: fishing distribution is proportional to B^Spat_targ. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
4 EffYears Years representing join-points (vertices) of time-varying effort. Vector. Non-negative real numbers
5 EffLower Lower bound on relative effort corresponding to EffYears. Vector. Non-negative real numbers
6 EffUpper Upper bound on relative effort corresponding to EffYears. Vector. Non-negative real numbers
7 Esd Additional inter-annual variability in fishing mortality rate. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
8 qinc Average percentage change in fishing efficiency (applicable only to forward projection and input controls). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
9 qcv Inter-annual variability in fishing efficiency (applicable only to forward projection and input controls). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
10 L5 Shortest length corresponding to 5 percent vulnerability. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
11 LFS Shortest length that is fully vulnerable to fishing. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
12 Vmaxlen The vulnerability of fish at Stock@Linf . Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Fraction
13 isRel Selectivity parameters in units of size-of-maturity (or absolute eg cm). Single value. Boolean.
14 LR5 Shortest length corresponding ot 5 percent retention. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
15 LFR Shortest length that is fully retained. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
16 Rmaxlen The retention of fish at Stock@Linf . Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
17 DR Discard rate - the fraction of caught fish that are discarded. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Fraction
18 SelYears (Optional) Years representing join-points (vertices) at which historical selectivity pattern changes. Vector. Positive real numbers
19 AbsSelYears (Optional) Calendar years corresponding with SelYears (eg 1951, rather than 1), used for plotting only. Vector (of same length as SelYears). Positive real numbers
20 L5Lower (Optional) Lower bound of L5 (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
21 L5Upper (Optional) Upper bound of L5 (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
22 LFSLower (Optional) Lower bound of LFS (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
23 LFSUpper (Optional) Upper bound of LFS (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
24 VmaxLower (Optional) Lower bound of Vmaxlen (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Fraction
25 VmaxUpper (Optional) Upper bound of Vmaxlen (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Fraction
26 CurrentYr The current calendar year (final year) of the historical simulations (eg 2011). Single value. Positive integer.
27 MPA (Optional) Matrix specifying spatial closures for historical years.
29 NA
31 NA
33 NA
35 NA

Obs

Slot Description
1 Name The name of the observation model object. Single value. Character string.
2 Cobs Log-normal catch observation error expressed as a coefficient of variation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
3 Cbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling the sampling of bias in catch observations for each simulation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
4 CAA_nsamp Number of catch-at-age observation per time step. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
5 CAA_ESS Effective sample size (independent age draws) of the multinomial catch-at-age observation error model. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive integers
6 CAL_nsamp Number of catch-at-length observation per time step. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive integers
7 CAL_ESS Effective sample size (independent length draws) of the multinomial catch-at-length observation error model. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive integers
8 Iobs Observation error in the relative abundance indices expressed as a coefficient of variation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
9 Ibiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling error in observations of relative abundance index. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
10 Btobs Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling error in observations of current stock biomass among years. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
11 Btbiascv Uniform-log bounds for sampling persistent bias in current stock biomass. Uniform-log distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
12 beta A parameter controlling hyperstability/hyperdepletion where values below 1 lead to hyperstability (an index that decreases slower than true abundance) and values above 1 lead to hyperdepletion (an index that decreases more rapidly than true abundance). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
13 LenMbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in length at 50 percent maturity. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
14 Mbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed natural mortality rate. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
15 Kbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed growth parameter K. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
16 t0biascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed t0. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
17 Linfbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed maximum length. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
18 LFCbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed length at first capture. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
19 LFSbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in length-at-full selection. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
20 FMSYbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in FMSY. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
21 FMSY_Mbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in FMSY/M. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
22 BMSY_B0biascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in BMSY relative to unfished. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
23 Irefbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in relative abundance index at BMSY. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
24 Brefbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in BMSY. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
25 Crefbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in MSY. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
26 Dbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in stock depletion. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
27 Dobs Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling error in observations of stock depletion among years. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
28 hbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in steepness. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
29 Recbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in recent recruitment strength. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
31 NA
33 NA
35 NA
37 NA

Imp

Slot Description
1 Name The name of the Implementation error object. Single value. Character string.
2 TACFrac Mean fraction of TAC taken. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real number.
3 TACSD Log-normal coefficient of variation in the fraction of Total Allowable Catch (TAC) taken. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers.
4 TAEFrac Mean fraction of TAE taken. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real number.
5 TAESD Log-normal coefficient of variation in the fraction of Total Allowable Effort (TAE) taken. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers.
6 SizeLimFrac The real minimum size that is retained expressed as a fraction of the size. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real number.
7 SizeLimSD Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling mismatch between a minimum size limit and the real minimum size retained. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers.
9 NA
11 NA
13 NA

OM

Slot Description
1 Name Name of the operating model
2 Agency Name of the agency responsible for the management of the fishery. Character string
3 Region Name of the general geographic region of the fishery. Character string
4 Sponsor Name of the organization who sponsored the OM. Character string
5 Latitude Latitude (decimal degrees). Negative values represent the South of the Equator. Numeric. Single value
6 Longitude Longitude (decimal degrees). Negative values represent the West of the Prime Meridian. Numeric. Single value
7 nsim The number of simulations
8 proyears The number of projected years
9 interval The assessment interval - how often would you like to update the management system?
10 pstar The percentile of the sample of the management recommendation for each method
11 maxF Maximum instantaneous fishing mortality rate that may be simulated for any given age class
12 reps Number of samples of the management recommendation for each method. Note that when this is set to 1, the mean value of the data inputs is used.
13 cpars A list of custom parameters. Time series are a matrix nsim rows by nyears columns. Single parameters are a vector nsim long
14 seed A random seed to ensure users can reproduce results exactly
15 Source A reference to a website or article from which parameters were taken to define the operating model
16 Common_Name Common name of the species. Character string
17 Species Scientific name of the species. Genus and species name. Character string
18 maxage The maximum age of individuals that is simulated (there is no plus group ). Single value. Positive integer
19 R0 The magnitude of unfished recruitment. Single value. Positive real number
20 M Natural mortality rate. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real number
21 M2 (Optional) Natural mortality rate at age. Vector of length maxage . Positive real number
22 Mexp Exponent of the Lorenzen function assuming an inverse relationship between M and weight. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers <= 0.
23 Msd Inter-annual variability in natural mortality rate expressed as a coefficient of variation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
24 Mgrad Mean temporal trend in natural mortality rate, expressed as a percentage change in M per year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
25 h Steepness of the stock recruit relationship. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Values from 1/5 to 1
26 SRrel Type of stock-recruit relationship. Single value, switch (1) Beverton-Holt (2) Ricker. Integer
27 Perr Process error, the CV of lognormal recruitment deviations. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
28 AC Autocorrelation in recruitment deviations rec(t)=ACrec(t-1)+(1-AC)sigma(t). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
29 Period (Optional) Period for cyclical recruitment pattern in years. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
30 Amplitude (Optional) Amplitude in deviation from long-term average recruitment during recruitment cycle (eg a range from 0 to 1 means recruitment decreases or increases by up to 100% each cycle). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. 0 < Amplitude < 1
31 Linf Maximum length. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
32 K von Bertalanffy growth parameter k. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
33 t0 von Bertalanffy theoretical age at length zero. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-positive real numbers
34 LenCV Coefficient of variation of length-at-age (assumed constant for all age classes). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
35 Ksd Inter-annual variability in growth parameter k. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
36 Kgrad Mean temporal trend in growth parameter k, expressed as a percentage change in k per year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
37 Linfsd Inter-annual variability in maximum length. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
38 Linfgrad Mean temporal trend in maximum length, expressed as a percentage change in Linf per year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
39 L50 Length at 50 percent maturity. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
40 L50_95 Length increment from 50 percent to 95 percent maturity. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
41 D Current level of stock depletion SSB(current)/SSB(unfished). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Fraction
42 a Length-weight parameter alpha. Single value. Positive real number
43 b Length-weight parameter beta. Single value. Positive real number
44 Size_area_1 The size of area 1 relative to area 2. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
45 Frac_area_1 The fraction of the unfished biomass in stock 1. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
46 Prob_staying The probability of inviduals in area 1 remaining in area 1 over the course of one year. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive fraction.
47 Fdisc Fraction of discarded fish that die. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
48 nyears The number of years for the historical spool-up simulation. Single value. Positive integer
49 Spat_targ Distribution of fishing in relation to spatial biomass: fishing distribution is proportional to B^Spat_targ. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Real numbers
50 EffYears Years representing join-points (vertices) of time-varying effort. Vector. Non-negative real numbers
51 EffLower Lower bound on relative effort corresponding to EffYears. Vector. Non-negative real numbers
52 EffUpper Upper bound on relative effort corresponding to EffYears. Vector. Non-negative real numbers
53 Esd Additional inter-annual variability in fishing mortality rate. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
54 qinc Average percentage change in fishing efficiency (applicable only to forward projection and input controls). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
55 qcv Inter-annual variability in fishing efficiency (applicable only to forward projection and input controls). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
56 L5 Shortest length corresponding to 5 percent vulnerability. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
57 LFS Shortest length that is fully vulnerable to fishing. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
58 Vmaxlen The vulnerability of fish at Stock@Linf. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Fraction
59 isRel Selectivity parameters in units of size-of-maturity (or absolute eg cm). Single value. Boolean.
60 LR5 Shortest length corresponding ot 5 percent retention. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
61 LFR Shortest length that is fully retained. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
62 Rmaxlen The retention of fish at Stock@Linf. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers
63 DR Discard rate - the fraction of caught fish that are discarded. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Fraction
64 SelYears (Optional) Years representing join-points (vertices) at which historical selectivity pattern changes. Vector. Positive real numbers
65 AbsSelYears (Optional) Calendar years corresponding with SelYears (eg 1951, rather than 1), used for plotting only. Vector (of same length as SelYears). Positive real numbers
66 L5Lower (Optional) Lower bound of L5 (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
67 L5Upper (Optional) Upper bound of L5 (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
68 LFSLower (Optional) Lower bound of LFS (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
69 LFSUpper (Optional) Upper bound of LFS (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Non-negative real numbers
70 VmaxLower (Optional) Lower bound of Vmaxlen (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Fraction
71 VmaxUpper (Optional) Upper bound of Vmaxlen (use ChooseSelect function to set these). Vector. Fraction
72 CurrentYr The current calendar year (final year) of the historical simulations (eg 2011). Single value. Positive integer. .
73 MPA (Optional) Matrix specifying spatial closures for historical years. Each row should contain year index (e.g 10 for 10th historical year) followed by fraction of area closed to fishing for each area. i.e. each row represents a change and the number of columns is nareas + 1. The spatial closures are assumed to remain in place for the future projections unless changed by a MP. Default (if left blank) is all areas are open to fishing in historical period.
74 Cobs Log-normal catch observation error expressed as a coefficient of variation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Non-negative real numbers

80 Iobs Observation error in the relative abundance indices expressed as a coefficient of variation. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
81 Ibiascv NOT CURRENTLY USED Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling error in observations of relative abundance index. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
82 Btobs Log-normal coefficient of variation controlling error in observations of current stock biomass among years. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
83 Btbiascv Uniform-log bounds for sampling persistent bias in current stock biomass. Uniform-log distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
84 beta A parameter controlling hyperstability/hyperdepletion where values below 1 lead to hyperstability (an index that decreases slower than true abundance) and values above 1 lead to hyperdepletion (an index that decreases more rapidly than true abundance). Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
85 LenMbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in length at 50 percent maturity. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
86 Mbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed natural mortality rate. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
87 Kbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed growth parameter K. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
88 t0biascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed t0. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
89 Linfbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed maximum length. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
90 LFCbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in observed length at first capture. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
91 LFSbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in length-at-full selection. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
92 FMSYbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in FMSY. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
93 FMSY_Mbiascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in FMSY/M. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
94 BMSY_B0biascv Log-normal coefficient of variation for sampling persistent bias in BMSY relative to unfished. Uniform distribution lower and upper bounds. Positive real numbers
